<div id="review_2258469301" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2258469301" />
    <a title="Sophie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4825553-sophie"><img alt="Sophie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608338927p2/4825553.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2258469301?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sophie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sophie" href="/user/show/4825553-sophie">Sophie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4825553-sophie?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4825553-sophie?shelf=arthurian-fantasy">arthurian-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2258469301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1706880842911959155">I&apos;ve had this book, along with the other two in the trilogy, on my shelf for ages. Since I had never actually read the synopsis in the inside cover, I had no idea what the book was about or what to expect. Within one chapter, I was hooked.<br/><br/>The writing is clear and the story is direct in this entry in the Arthurian fantasy genre. &quot;Hawk of May&quot; is narrated by Gwalchmai (better know as Gawain in English--Gwalchmai is the Welsh version) and tells the first part of his journey from bullied adolescent </span>
  <span id="freeText1706880842911959155" style="display:none">I've had this book, along with the other two in the trilogy, on my shelf for ages. Since I had never actually read the synopsis in the inside cover, I had no idea what the book was about or what to expect. Within one chapter, I was hooked.<br /><br />The writing is clear and the story is direct in this entry in the Arthurian fantasy genre. "Hawk of May" is narrated by Gwalchmai (better know as Gawain in English--Gwalchmai is the Welsh version) and tells the first part of his journey from bullied adolescent to one of the most renowned knights of Camelot. A poor athlete and not a very promising warrior, this second son of a warrior king escapes from the evil clutches of dark sorceress Margawse to become a champion of "The Light" and earn a place by King Arthur's side.<br /><br />It was a quick read, and the part I enjoyed best was all of the Welsh and Irish Gaelic place names and proper names. I had a lot of fun making connections between the traditional Welsh names and the English transliterations that are more familiar to the casual reader. It certainly reignited my love for the Arthurian mythos, a love I thought I had outgrown in childhood. In fact, shortly after I began "Hawk of May", I started (re)reading "The Mists of Avalon", as a nice accompaniment to Bradshaw's work.<br /><br />My only criticism is that Gwalchmai's journey seems to lack the true grit of the traditional coming of age story. It has most--if not all--of the tropes of a standard Bildungsroman, but I feel that Gwalchai's achievement of skill and maturity was not very hard won. I would have expected more of a struggles, more of a fight. I don't want to include a spoiler, but I will say that the "turning point", where the protagonist begins his transformation from callow youth to self-actualized hero was a bit underwhelming and relied too much upon being the 'Chosen One'. Despite this, "Hawk of May" was a fun read and I would recommend it to anyone looking to emmerse themselves in a quick fantasy story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1706880842911959155" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


