<span id="freeTextContainer16737655378906203047">Did not love it; did not like it much. In terms of my personal opinion, it&apos;s probably a one-star since I did finally skim about twenty pages to move it along and just have done with it. I read the last chapter. The big reveal at the end was obvious from the beginning. I kept waiting for something wonderful to happen, and . . . no. <br/><br/>To be completely fair, it&apos;s not badly written and it&apos;s hard to reveal anything surprising in the Arthur legend. I can see how someone might love it. The Light/Darkness</span>
  <span id="freeText16737655378906203047" style="display:none">Did not love it; did not like it much. In terms of my personal opinion, it's probably a one-star since I did finally skim about twenty pages to move it along and just have done with it. I read the last chapter. The big reveal at the end was obvious from the beginning. I kept waiting for something wonderful to happen, and . . . no. <br /><br />To be completely fair, it's not badly written and it's hard to reveal anything surprising in the Arthur legend. I can see how someone might love it. The Light/Darkness struggle was not inaccurate in terms of the Christian aspects of the legend, but the claim of "philosophy" was worthy of a short story, not a novel. I have read many versions of the Arthurian legends. After a lengthy career writing romances, Mary Stewart wrote a series with Merlin as Roman-educated. Marion Zimmer Bradley wrote what she called "pot boiler" fantasies, she wrote <i>Mists of Avalon</i>, giving center stage to women and the original inhabitants. <br /><br />There are wonderful takes on Arthur, this is not one of them. Love the cover.</span>
